07658nam a22007575i 9781447309079DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20122012xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814473090797 a10.51952/97814473090792doi  a(DE-B1597)646209  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a305.8522200aCritical Geographies of Childhood and Youth :bContemporary Policy and Practice /ced. by Peter Kraftl, John Horton, Faith Tucker. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables, figures and boxes -- tNotes on contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tEditors’ introduction: critical geographies of childhood and youth -- t(Inter)national youth policies: politics and practices of spatial translation -- tMaking ‘youth publics’ and ‘neuro-citizens’: critical geographies of contemporary educational practice in the UK -- tYouth policy, neoliberalism and transnational governmentality: a case study of Lesotho and Malawi -- t‘Brighter futures, greener lives’: children and young people in UK sustainable development policy -- tPlaces to go, things to do and people to see: space and activity in English youth work policy -- tEducation and employment policies: learning beyond schools and schools beyond learning -- tThe place of aspiration in UK widening participation policy: moving up or moving beyond? -- tSchool choice versus social cohesion: examining the ways education policies shape children’s geographies in the UK -- tLunchtime lock-in: territorialisation and UK school meals policies -- tInformal education in compulsory schooling in the UK: humanising moments, utopian spaces? -- tIntervening in ‘everyday life’: scales, practices and the ‘spatial imagination’ in youth policy and professional practice -- tA free for all? Scale and young people’s participation in UK transport planning -- tIncluding young people in heritage conservation in southern Brazilian cities: the case of Pelotas -- tAnchoring identity: the construction of responsibility for and by young offenders in the US -- tParenting policy and the geographies of friendship: encounters in an English Sure Start Children’s Centre -- tYouth homelessness policy in Wales: improving housing rights and addressing geographical wrongs -- tChildhood in South Africa in the time of HIV/AIDS: reconsidering policy and practice -- tConcluding reflections -- tConcluding reflections: what next and where next for critical geographies of youth policy and practice? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis original book explores the importance of geographical processes for policies and professional practices related to childhood and youth. Contributors from a wide range of disciplinary backgrounds explore how concepts such as place, scale, mobility and boundary-making are important for policies and practices in diverse contexts. Chapters present both comprehensive cutting-edge academic research and critical reflections by practitioners working in diverse contexts, giving the volume wide appeal. The focus on the role of geographical processes in policies and professional practices that affect young people provides new, critical insights into contemporary issues and debates. The contributions show how local and national concerns remain central to many youth programmes; they also highlight how youth policies are becoming increasingly globalised. Examples are taken from the UK, the Americas and Africa. The chapters are informed by and advance contemporary theoretical approaches in human geography, sociology, anthropology and youth work, and will be of interest to academics and higher-level students in those disciplines. The book will also appeal to policy-makers and professionals who work with young people, encouraging them to critically reflect upon the role of geographical processes in their own work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChildrenxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnsell, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzevedo, Laura Novo de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartwright, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColquhoun, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Bethan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHajdu, Flora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoneyford, Emma-Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJupp, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraftl, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraftl, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMackie, Peter K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarandet, Elodie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorman, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPike, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo